Q1. What is the difference between Docker and Kubernetes?
----------------------------------------------------------------

Answer:

Docker is a container platform, while Kubernetes is a container
orchestration platform.

Containers are ephemeral in nature — they can go down for
multiple reasons, and when they do, the application becomes
unavailable to end users. To avoid this, you move to a container
orchestration platform like Kubernetes, which offers:

  • Auto-healing — if a pod goes down, Kubernetes automatically
    restarts it.

  • Auto-scaling — Kubernetes can scale pods up or down based
    on load.

  • Cluster-level resilience — unlike Docker, which is a single-
    node platform, Kubernetes combines multiple virtual machines
    into a cluster. If one node goes down, Kubernetes moves the
    pod to a different node automatically.

  • Enterprise capabilities — load balancing, Custom Resource
    Definitions (CRDs), and support for third-party controllers
    like Ingress controllers that extend its capabilities.

In short: Docker runs containers on a single machine; Kubernetes
manages containers at scale across a cluster of machines.

