Q4. What is the difference between a Docker container
    and a Kubernetes Pod?
----------------------------------------------------------------

Answer:

A Docker container is a running instance of a container image
on a single machine.

A Pod is the lowest-level deployable unit in Kubernetes. It is
essentially a runtime specification written in a YAML file that
defines everything a container needs to run. Key differences:

  • A pod can hold one or multiple containers.
  • Containers within the same pod share the same network
    (they can communicate via localhost) and the same storage
    volumes.
  • A pod abstracts the container and gives Kubernetes the
    metadata it needs to manage, schedule, and restart it.

Simply put: a Pod is a wrapper or runtime specification around
one or more containers, managed by Kubernetes.

