Q5. What is a Namespace in Kubernetes?
----------------------------------------------------------------

Answer:

A Kubernetes Namespace is a logical isolation of resources
within a single cluster.

In a real-world scenario, a company may have 20 different teams
working on 20 different microservices — all deployed on the same
Kubernetes cluster. Creating a separate cluster for each project
is not practical in production.

Namespaces solve this by letting multiple teams share one
cluster while remaining logically separated:

  • Each team or project gets its own namespace (e.g.,
    namespace-a, namespace-b).
  • Resources, deployments, and services in namespace-a are
    isolated from namespace-b.
  • Access is controlled using RBAC (Role-Based Access Control).
  • Network policies and resource quotas can be applied per
    namespace.

One-line answer: A Kubernetes Namespace is a logical boundary
that allows multiple teams or projects to coexist on the same
cluster without interfering with each other.

